abstract: With the final gavel banging down Wednesday on impeachment, President Donald Trump barreled ahead in his reelection fight with a united Republican Party behind him, and emboldened by reassuring poll numbers and chaos in the Democratic race to replace him.
snippet: With the final gavel banging down Wednesday on impeachment, President Donald Trump barreled ahead in his reelection fight with a united Republican Party behind him, and emboldened by reassuring poll numbers and chaos in the Democratic race to repl...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With the final gavel banging down Wednesday on impeachment, President Donald Trump barreled ahead in his reelection fight with a united Republican Party behind him, and emboldened by reassuring poll numbers and chaos in the Democratic race to replace him.
headline_main: Trump Barrels Into 2020 Campaign, Emboldened After Acquittal
headline_print_headline: Trump Barrels Into 2020 Campaign, Emboldened After Acquittal

abstract: The bill he supported is limited; it works by allowing people to borrow from their future selves.
snippet: The bill he supported is limited; it works by allowing people to borrow from their future selves.
lead_paragraph: President Trump called for paid family leave in the State of the Union on Tuesday, the first Republican president to do so. But the bill he supported does not offer what has generally been considered paid family leave.

headline_main: Senate Votes to Acquit President Trump

abstract: Readers discuss what it means for the president (“he can get away with anything”), and for the country. One says in jest that if democracy is over, he has a monarch to offer.

abstract: President Donald Trump was gone, the House lights were dimming, and House Speaker Nancy Pelosi looked up to her friends and family in the gallery overhead.  She held up the speech she had shredded behind Trump's back, on live television. She put her hand to her heart, dipped her head and gave a little bow.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Donald Trump was gone, the House lights were dimming, and House Speaker Nancy Pelosi looked up to her friends and family in the gallery overhead. She held up the speech she had shredded behind Trump's back, on live television. She put her hand to her heart, dipped her head and gave a little bow.
headline_main: Impeachment Done, Pelosi Unburdens Herself About Trump

headline_main: In Private, Republicans Admit They Acquitted Trump Out of Fear

abstract: As Republicans rallied behind President Trump, Senator Mitt Romney of Utah, the party’s 2012 presidential nominee, joined Democrats in voting to convict, the only senator to cross party lines.
snippet: As Republicans rallied behind President Trump, Senator Mitt Romney of Utah, the party’s 2012 presidential nominee, joined Democrats in voting to convict, the only senator to cross party lines.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After five months of hearings, investigations and revelations about President Trump’s dealings with Ukraine, a divided United States Senate acquitted him on Wednesday of charges that he abused his power and obstructed Congress to aid his own re-election, bringing an acrimonious impeachment trial to its expected end.
